Here's the recommended approach:

**1. Abstract the HTTP dependency**

Inject `HttpClient` (or a typed client) into your tool classes via constructor injection rather than creating it inline.

```csharp
public class MyTool(HttpClient httpClient)
{
    public async Task<string> GetDataAsync(string id)
    {
        var response = await httpClient.GetAsync($"/api/items/{id}");
        return await response.Content.ReadAsStringAsync();
    }
}
```

**2. Create the test project**

```bash
dotnet new xunit -n MyMcpServer.Tests
cd MyMcpServer.Tests
dotnet add reference ../MyMcpServer/MyMcpServer.csproj
```

**3. Mock HTTP with `MockHttpMessageHandler`**

Use a custom or library-provided handler (e.g., [RichardSzalay.MockHttp](https://github.com/richardszalay/mockhttp)):

```csharp
// No external dependency needed — just subclass:
public class FakeHandler : HttpMessageHandler
{
    private readonly HttpResponseMessage _response;
    public FakeHandler(HttpResponseMessage response) => _response = response;

    protected override Task<HttpResponseMessage> SendAsync(
        HttpRequestMessage request, CancellationToken ct)
        => Task.FromResult(_response);
}

public class MyToolTests
{
    [Fact]
    public async Task GetDataAsync_ReturnsExpectedJson()
    {
        var fakeResponse = new HttpResponseMessage(HttpStatusCode.OK)
        {
            Content = new StringContent("""{"id":"1","name":"Test"}""")
        };
        var client = new HttpClient(new FakeHandler(fakeResponse))
        {
            BaseAddress = new Uri("https://fake.api")
        };

        var tool = new MyTool(client);
        var result = await tool.GetDataAsync("1");

        Assert.Contains("Test", result);
    }
}
```

**Key principles:**

| Concern | Approach |
|---|---|
| Decouple from real API | Inject `HttpClient` via DI |
| Fake responses | Swap in a custom `HttpMessageHandler` |
| Test tool logic only | Assert on the tool's return value / side effects |
| Test error paths | Return `4xx`/`5xx` from the fake handler |

This avoids any real network calls while fully exercising your tool logic.
